531249.clubName: Lambda Theta Alpha Latin Sorority, Inc.

857643.clubName: Sigma Lambda Gamma National Sorority, Inc.

778479.description: .dev (pronounced “dot dev") is the essential club for students trying to break into the tech industry, whether they are interested in software engineering, UI/UX design, or quantitative/programmatic trading.

335865.description: 64 Squares Chess Club is dedicated to promoting chess in the Northwestern community by providing a comfortable and fun chess-playing environment.

541024.description: The largest student group on campus, has provided Northwestern University undergraduates with top-notch large-scale entertainment programming since its inception in 1969.

497559.clubName: Academy of Music and Arts for Special Education
497559.description: Teaches individuals with learning disabilities to engage with music and arts on Saturday mornings on campus.

219741.description: Primary mental health awareness and advocacy group at Northwestern. We focus our efforts on informing students about mental wellness, creating a dialogue surrounding mental health and illness, and reducing the stigmas associated with it.

465431.description: Advancement for the Undocumented Community (AUC) is a student organization dedicated to providing resources and support for undocumented student and students with undocumented family members.

161958.description: A community for African students and promotes African awareness to the greater Northwestern community.

938102.description: African Dance Group at Northwestern University to promote African culture by showcasing traditional and modern African-themed dance moves and music.

700690.description: A non-competitive South Asian fusion dance team that hopes to provide dancers with a space to learn, grow, and create.

288112.description: The world's largest youth leadership organization, full of globally minded young leaders. People who want to grow their own potential while contributing to something much greater than themselves.

601815.description: Constructive debate on basic principles and contemporary issues in foreign, economic and national security policy at Northwestern University.

733601.description: Aims to unite and support its members towards an advancement of an empowered, productive Latino/a/x presence at NU; Alianza is a cultural, educational, and social programming body.

339350.description: Brings together undergraduates who are passionate about volunteering in a clinical setting (which will be located at Northwestern Memorial Hospital & Prentice's Women Hospital)

209108.description: Unites students across Northwestern's campus by creating spaces for critical discourse on current events in and in relation to Africa

516058.description: Alpha Kappa Psi was founded in 1904 at New York University on the principles of promoting institutions of business education, developing future leaders and fostering appreciation for higher ideals in business. Today the fraternity has grown to become the oldest and largest professional business fraternity in the world. With nearly 240,000 initiated members and more than 200 chapters, it is among the 20 largest college fraternities.

861318.description: Sigma Chapter at Northwestern is comprised of over 40 active members who focus on leadership, friendship and service. The major focus of our operations is service opportunities. Members help out on campus and in the local community. We have a variety of involvements including Campus Kitchens, Challah for Hunger, Center for Independent Futures, and Housing Opportunities for Women. We also have fellowship activities like dinners, a formal, and trips downtown. Members get to know each other and have fun hanging out and doing service with their friends.

729442.description: Alternative Student Breaks seeks to educate Northwestern students of all majors and backgrounds by sponsoring service-learning trips during academic breaks in fall, winter, and spring. Service-learning is the heart of ASB, which promotes a critical approach to social justice and service that centers the communities affected by a social issue.    ASB trips take place during the first week of winter break and over the course of spring break. Groups of up to twelve students engage with community partners and social issues across the country to deep dive into the social issue and the work people are doing to address it.   ASB also offers class trips! Students participating in class trips take a peer-led, for-credit course taught by seasoned ASB veterans before heading out to work with the social issue they just spent the previous quarter learning about. These classes are a great way to deepen your learning about a social issue near to your heart, and also meet wonderful, passionate peers. For winter break class trips, the class takes place during the fall quarter. For spring break class trips, the classes take place during winter quarter. All these fantastic classes are also pass/fail!   You can get involved with ASB in several ways. Join our listserv to receive applications for upcoming trips by sending a request to asb@u.northwestern.edu. If you would like to really get hands-on with what ASB does, look for applications to be a trip leader or an exec member. Details for these positions will be sent out over the listserv and posted on our main website at www.northwesternasb.com

173767.description: The American Medical Women’s Association Northwestern University chapter aims to foster an enriching environment for women in science and the medical profession. We hope to give back to the community through a variety of events spreading awareness about women’s health issues.  Our Objectives:   …to provide peer mentorship to undergraduate students pursuing careers in science and medicine …to spread awareness about women’s health issues on campus and the community at large …to create a positive space for women pursuing careers in science and medicine

525304.description: The Society of Asian Scientists and Engineers (SASE) seeks to advance Asian-heritage scientific and engineering professionals and help achieve their full potential. SASE members help create and partake in a variety of cultural and professional development activities as well as volunteering work to help the surrounding community. SASE is open to all majors, races, ethnicities, and genders, and is an organization where students can connect over an appreciation of Pan-Asian culture and support each other.

620060.description: AMPED is a weekend music mentorship program that connects Northwestern students with incarcerated young men at the Cook County Juvenile Temporary Detention Center. The “Saturday practice sessions” are offered for 2 hours every Saturday in the CCJTDC music lab to young men who show interest, talent, and desire to hone the skills they learn in their once a week classes. The sessions are facilitated by undergraduate & graduate mentors from Northwestern University, who provide musical assistance and support for the students. AMPED aims to help develop the students’ music composition skills through the use of GarageBand software while offering structured and trusting mentorships between the NU students and CCJTDC students.

485681.description: Applause for a Cause is a philanthropic, student-run film production company. Our members annually write, produce, direct, and edit a feature length film (~90 minutes) to premiere in May and to raise donations for the chosen beneficiary of that year. In the past we have worked with local and national organizations including the Make-A-Wish foundation, the Howard Area Community Center, and Connections for the Homeless. Our production timeline starts in the summer with screenplay submissions. Then once a script is chosen, we hold crew petitions and casting auditions when the school year starts in fall. Production occurs during the winter, and finally we edit and roll out the red carpet in the spring. We are completely student run, and encourage students of all studies and film backgrounds (even if you have none at all) to join our organization so that you can experience college film-making and meet some great people along the way. Not a student? We accept year-long support, advice, and donations and if you are in town, we invite you to attend the premiere. It takes a village to make a feature, so we encourage you to participate in any way you can!

612618.description: The Arch Society is a group of student ambassadors sponsored by the Northwestern Alumni Association (NAA). Members will support and develop university-related programs and community-wide events to strengthen the relationships between alumni, students, faculty, and staff and to foster a sense of pride and community. Meetings occur once a month during the academic year with additional meetings or program support occurring as needed. Candidates are chosen and serve as representatives throughout their time at Northwestern. Each member of the Arch Society will serve on one of the four committees: (1) Class Programming Committee shall be responsible for class-specific programming to increase NAA touch points with current students between Wildcat Welcome and Senior Week (i.e., Sophomore Welcome Back, Senior Class Picnic) (2) Marketing & Outreach Committee shall be responsible for social media presence/content creation and outreach to student groups on campus (i.e., supporting social justice and mental health initiatives) (3) Traditions Committee shall be responsible for promoting current traditions and initiating new traditions (i.e., NU Day @ Wrigley, Northwestern Night at the Art Institute) (4) Homecoming Committee shall support Homecoming programs, recruitment, and student-alumni engagement initiatives (i.e., Homecoming Social)

954059.description: Tea has always been a significant part of many cultures around the world, and tea can also be a bridge between people from different countries and races. Usually accompanied by art, cuisine, and literature, tea helps us understand the culture of a country from the everyday life of its people. Our aim is to create an open and friendly environment for people to learn about tea and tea culture in the world and to provide an opportunity for students to talk and learn about different cultures. During our weekly meetings our we will introduce different kinds of tea from a variety of countries. Basic techniques and knowledge of tea ceremony will be taught through practice and appreciation. Students can learn about the cultures and histories of different countries while enjoying the aroma and the taste of exquisite tea.

494805.description: About Art Union is Northwestern’s premier art club. We aspire to promote and develop a community of Northwestern artists, helping to nurture relationships, artistic skills, and various talents from a diverse network of students, through intentional art-making and sharing of the love of art practice. AU seeks to emphasize the art practice of artists at Northwestern, using their passion and skills for art to create a strong community within NU. From sketching and drawing nights, painting sessions, trips to the museums, and chill hangouts at local areas to simply get together and make art, we want AU to nurture the general public’s love for art practice, creating an art-loving family for all.

489701.description: ARTivate is a community arts engagement initiative that aims to use art to create a more diverse and interconnected community, provide safe spaces, and improve the overall well-being of individuals. We plan to host on and off-campus art workshops and guest speakers to reach this goal and to create a centralized digital platform to ensure accessibility and transparency of our program. We believe that art empowers and heals. We hope to share our love for the arts with both our NU and Chicagoland communities, while striving to create positive change through the arts.  Our social justice arts initiative hopes to implement an art engagement program that would allow students and faculty to branch out and engage students at NU and neighboring schools in the performing and visual arts. This effort can be an effective way for the many NU students who are passionate about art to relieve stress while giving back to and learning about their local communities. Our program focuses strongly on providing a space for students to escape the rapid lifestyle that we constantly embody and extend the passions of students to the larger Evanston community. Through our efforts, we hope to highlight the importance of acknowledging and respecting the arts in our daily lives. We will provide students with the opportunity to embrace their passion or find a new passion for the arts.

731631.description: Arts Alliance is the oldest and largest student arts group at Northwestern University. Founded in 1974 by a collection of arts groups looking to share space, Arts Alliance has grown to become one of the largest student arts organizations in the country. Its annual season consists of three mainstage shows and two Mee-Ow Improv & Sketch Comedy shows. Arts Alliance Executive Board consists of seventeen members committed to bringing accessible, exciting, and entertaining theatrical experiences to the Northwestern and Evanston communities. All Arts Alliance programming revolves around the three pillars of our mission statement: art that is easy to relate to, art that is easy to speak with, and art that is easy to reach. We tell stories that resonate with our community members by delivering theatre that they want to see without physical or financial barriers.  Arts Alliance is a non-profit student arts organization committed to providing diverse, accessible, and fulfilling artistic experiences to enrich the Northwestern University community. Arts Alliance is rooted in its long-standing traditions and continues to seek out new artistic opportunities. It provides a positive atmosphere in which students can learn and work alongside a committed and supportive board to create professional-quality productions.

456978.description: About In recognition of the heterogeneity of Asian America, the Asian Pacific American Coalition is a sociopolitical group that provides a space for students who share an identity shaped around their politics to connect, learn, organize, and ultimately resist systems of domination. From our unique position as similarly racialized peoples, we build community and raise awareness of historical, social, and political issues that affect marginalized communities at large due to the interconnected nature of oppressive power structures through the following: Collective learning Support systems Programming, both educational and advocacy-based Coalition-building APAC’s history began in 1991, under the name of Asian American Advisory Board (AAAB). It started out as an umbrella organization for all of the Asian/Asian American student groups to coordinate and guide their different activities. In 1992, the AAAB gained A-status from the Northwestern’s Associated Student Government. The organization began to make headlines in 1995 when APAC organized a successful hunger strike fighting for the creation of an Asian American Studies Program. The incident garnered public support from universities all over the country and has served to inspire a new generation of young Asian Americans. In 2003, AAAB officially changed its name to The Asian Pacific American Coalition (APAC). The new name was intended to be more inclusive and reflective of the diverse and heterogeneous mix of Asian America. Along with the name change, APAC remade its constitution and redefined its mission statement towards a more holistic outlook, making commitments to community building by addressing political, cultural, and social issues of Asian America both within our own community and with the rest of NU’s population through various programs and events. In the past, APAC has hosted events such as Asian American History Month, a screening of Better Luck Tomorrow with cast and director Justin Lin, the annual Mr. PanAsia, Powderpuff football, Espresso Expressions, and speakers such as actor George Takei, comedian Margaret Cho, music video director Joseph Kahn, SuChin Pak of MTV, Japanese Breakfast, and Alok Vaid-Menon.   APAC strives to achieve the following: Commit to accessibility and inclusion, especially with regard to non-East Asian communities Recognize differences in experience within the umbrella of Asian, Asian American, and Pacific Islander peoples, as well as the experiences of multiracial peoples Engage and mobilize the student community through activism and advocacy Undertake intersectional grassroots activism and advocacy in the larger Northwestern community, Evanston, and Chicago Foster collective healing from historical, intergenerational, and individual trauma Empower individuals with marginalized identities If you are interested in joining APAC, interest forms are open near the beginning of every quarter -- keep an eye out on the FB page or send us an email at apac@u.northwestern.edu for updates!

588503.description: ASG is the Associated Student Government of Northwestern, a group of undergraduate students devoted to working on behalf of the Northwestern community. ASG discusses and acts on ways to make Northwestern an overall better experience for students. We work with Northwestern administrators to bring change to the university, but we also provide services directly to students. ASG is comprised of a student Senate – broadly representative of the varied student interests at Northwestern – an executive board, and 14 working committees that address issues affecting student life, academics, relations with Evanston, student groups, and more. ASG believes in building a better Northwestern.

663638.clubName: Association for Women in Sports Media

505530.clubName: Association of Latino Professionals for America

892033.clubName: Association of Undergraduate Women in Science

624593.description: Aviation Club helps aviation enthusiasts at Northwestern explore their interest in and expand their knowledge of aviation, including, but not limited to, general, commercial, and military aviation. It fosters interests in students new to aviation by offering a place to explore it in a supportive, knowledgeable, and connected environment. We help Northwestern students connect with fellow aviators to expand their network of colleagues on campus, providing more opportunities to share and participate in their passion with others. We also help Northwestern students interested in a career in aviation connect with advisors and opportunities to pursue their goals during and after college. Aviation is a very cost-prohibitive activity. We want to make it available to all Northwestern students in as many ways as possible. This can be achieved in many forms, and we are excited to build on our current plans to bring it to Northwestern students as best as possible.

458934.description: B. Burlesque is a dance interest group that serves to teach burlesque dance to students of color and showcase their performances in the annual burlesque show during winter quarter. Promoting body and sex positivity, B. Burlesque offers workshops led by professional burlesque dancers and trips to burlesque shows to get a better understanding of the art. Through 2 months of rehearsals, students will prepare for the annual show to showcase their unique routines.

255695.description: The Baja SAE team's goal is to enrich the Northwestern experience through the production of a competitive off-road racing vehicle by inspiring creative automotive design, forging marketable leadership and technical skills, and building a close-knit engineering community. The one-man, dune buggy type car must be prepared to face the most rugged terrain—rocks, creeks, snow, jumps, and mud—and keep their driver safe through all driving conditions including a roll over. The team consists of students, mostly from McCormick, who simply like to build cars and play in the mud.

571549.clubName: Ballet Folklórico Mexicano: Ritmo de Mis Ancestros
571549.description: Ballet Folklórico Mexicano: Ritmo de Mis Ancestros was established in 2012 by 6 freshmen Chicanas to create a space at Northwestern that made them feel comfortable enough to share and embrace their artistic side, their culture, and their roots. We strive to critically preserve our Mexican culture by showcasing folklórico at Northwestern and the surrounding communities and to increase awareness of Mexican ancestry and to serve as a catalyst for others to take pride in their own backgrounds.

113621.description: About BLAST (Ballroom, Latin, and Swing Team) is an undergraduate partner dancing community. Our club is split into two main seasons - a competition season (fall - mid-winter) and a show season (mid-winter - spring), interspersed with social dance classes and workshops. New members are welcome to join at any point of the year, with no prior experience necessary to participate in either season. The dancesport dance classes are open to anyone and begin in the fall shortly after new student week. Auditions for the show occur early in Winter quarter and then subsequent rehearsals will occur throughout the year until showtime in Spring.  Classes, workshops, and social dance opportunities range in style from social dances like swing, salsa, or blues to more formal ballroom dances like waltz and tango. Our goal as an organization is to create a partner dancing community here at Northwestern. All dancers are welcome to attend our classes, workshops, and social events. If you want to get more involved, the best ways to become a formal member of BLAST is to regularly show up to dancesport classes and actively participate in either the competitive or performance seasons.

586514.description: The Northwestern University chapter of Be The Match On Campus aims to increase awareness of the need for more young registry members, educate others about the under representation of ethnic minorities in the registry, and hold campus-wide marrow donor registry drives to give the entire student body the opportunity to join in this global effort.  We welcome any student to join! In Be the Match, we partner with other groups to host events, have fundraising activities, hold registry drives, host speakers, and more. Members will be involved in planning and holding events. For more information, feel free to contact us or check out our facebook page!

456024.description: Best Buddies is an international nonprofit organization dedicated to enhancing the lives of those with intellectual and/or physical disabilities by providing opportunities for one-to-one friendships, integrated employment, and leadership.  It was founded in 1989 by Anthony Kennedy Shriver. Each member of Northwestern's Best Buddies chapter is matched with an adult with disabilities. The buddy pair maintains regular contact throughout the year and meets several times a quarter for fun activities and themed outings. The chapter also promotes disability awareness on campus and throughout the community.

854780.description: Bhakti Yoga Society provides students the opportunity to experience yoga and spiritual culture from ancient India through a blend of yoga classes, small group discussions, meditation sessions, vegetarian cooking classes and speaker events that provide ancient prescriptions for modern maladies. Bhakti Yoga is the Vedic Science of connecting with the Higher Consciousness through devotion, bringing about genuine care for all people and things. People of all backgrounds are welcome! We meet on Fridays at 6:00 p.m. for yoga, guided meditation, discussions and dinner.

402496.description: The purpose of this organization shall be to build a community with biology students and provide biology students a resource to get involved with biology outside of the classroom.

741045.description: The Biomedimedical Engineering Society (BMES) at Northwestern University offers the chance to establish leadership skills, networking, and career development opportunities. BMES also facilitates community among biomedical engineering undergrads through social events and opportunities to interact with faculty in a casual setting.

884599.description: A collective of students, representative of members that both do and do not hold formal leadership positions in Black student organizations, pulled together to identify an event based on a community need. This event was intended to mirror other Northwestern-funded student formal affairs- with students dressing up and going to an off-campus venue for an evening of entertainment, food, and fun. The Black community has not had an event like this in recent years. Most formals or balls that occur within the Black community are hosted by Black Greek-letter organizations. This formal is unique because it is not affiliated with any student organization in the community and aims to create an inclusive space. This formal is in celebration of the Black community, and seeks to fulfill the needs expressed in the Black Student Experience Report.

578711.description: The Black Mentorship Program (BMP) is a mentorship program for Black identifying undergraduate students at Northwestern. We believe our mission is to improve the undergraduate experience of Black students at Northwestern through mentorship, community building, racial identity development, and engagement with community resources. During its pilot and subsequent years, the program will hold regular meetings throughout the school year with topics ranging from study skills and getting acclimated to college life to what it means to be Black at Northwestern. We are student led and hope to be an asset to the broader Northwestern community by creating a strong Black community and producing confident Black student leaders. Our mission is to improve the undergraduate experience of Black students at Northwestern through mentorship, community building, racial identity development, and engagement with community resources.

754476.description: The purpose of BlackBoard Magazine is to provide a space for Black creatives to publish their work concerning Black experiences on Northwestern's campus, in the United States and internationally. Additionally, BlackBoard Magazine aims to fill a void within journalism and other student-led publications on Northwestern's campus by celebrating Blackness and viewing Black stories as valuable and newsworthy. In this way, both Black folks and Black art are each viewed as important and, therefore, given their own personal space.

666706.description: The Block Student Advisory Board (BSAB) is a crossroads between the Block Museum and the campus community: we are a group of students with diverse backgrounds of study (art history to engineering) who share a love of art and interest in connecting art to our lives on and off campus. The BSAB seeks to bring a multifaceted range of students into the museum to develop new ways to engage the student body and the local arts community through planning and marketing creative events inspired by the museum's exhibitions and collection.

319416.description: Blockchain Group aims to foster a healthy and active ecosystem in Northwestern/Chicago and solidify our community on the map as a strong hub for blockchain technology. We work towards this vision by doing the following: provide a gateway for interested students to learn about blockchain technology organize speaker events that feature leaders in the industry work on portfolio-worthy technical and non-technical blockchain projects  collaborate with enterprises to empower our ecosystem

424599.description: Boomshaka is Northwestern University's premier drum, dance, and rhythm ensemble. Entirely student written, directed, and produced, Boomshaka has established a reputation for consistently delivering energetic and inspiring performances. We combine dance styles such as hip-hop and contemporary with various forms of percussion, using everything from sticks, poles, and buckets to our hands and feet. Our performers come from a variety of backgrounds and have a number of areas of artistic expertise, ranging from classical music composition and formal dance training to free style rapping and break dancing. We blend our unique talents and experiment with new mediums of expression to create a performance like none other!  Check us out on Youtube, Facebook, Instagram, or on our website.

501955.description: Our organization aims to educate the student body on the importance of bee conservation as well as provide a space in which students can collaborate and communicate to achieve a greater goal. We hope to be able to spread awareness about the decline in bee populations over the past decade and educate students at Northwestern on ways in which they can help the environment. We also hope to fundraise for bee conservation efforts.

152880.description: The Brazilian Student Association (BRASA) aims to establish prolific and long-lasting relationships between American universities and Brazil, thereby creating a platform through which Brazilian students in the United States – and non-Brazilian students willing to be involved – can act to improve Brazil. In addition, BRASA aims to promote the understanding of Brazilian culture, professional opportunities, and the Portuguese language.  A Associação Brasileira de Estudantes (BRASA) visa estabelecer relações prolíficas e duradouras entre universidades americanas e o Brasil, assim criando uma plataforma através da qual estudantes brasileiros nos Estados Unidos, e estudantes não brasileiros que desejam se envolver, podem atuar para melhorar o Brasil. Adicionalmente, a BRASA tem como objetivo promover o entendimento da cultura brasileira, oportunidades profissionais e da língua portuguesa.

770777.description: Like puzzles, cards, communication games, epic nerdy trash-talk, and ultimate contests of skill? Welcome to the world of bridge-- the world's most exciting card game!! Come join bridge clubs on Sundays at the Norris Student Center! Players of any experience level are welcome, and our members are ready and able to teach the game to any new players. Any member of the Northwestern or Evanston communities is welcome to join every week.  We'll be saying hello to new members, including a fun "Learn Bridge in a Day!" Presentation by club members intended for players whom have never played bridge in their lives, as well as doing free play. Information will be given about general meetings, the bridge scene at Northwestern and in the Chicago area, and the game itself! Looking forward to seeing you there! --- We also have a competitive team that meets separately, to play in the ACBL Collegiate Bridgebowl Competition. The past four years, we've made it to the national finals!! For information on our collegiate team come to initial meetings in September or email Sarik at sarikgoyal2021@u.northwestern.edu.

450413.description: Bridge Out’s purpose is to serve as a bridge from the Northwestern campus to non-profit organizations in the Chicago area. Northwestern has an abundance of ambitious students willing to volunteer time as well as an incredible amount of intellectual talent and performance talent that could aide non-profit organizations. In the current Northwestern community, producers of individual student groups, or individuals, are often tasked with forming partnerships and creating opportunities for Northwestern students to volunteer outside the community. We feel this results in many excellent partnerships being unexplored and hope to simplify the process.

403109.description: Brown Sugar is the nation's premiere South Asian-interest co-ed a cappella group. Founded in 1999 by two Northwestern students looking to embrace their South Asian roots, Brown Sugar performs a refreshing mix of South Asian and Western music, ranging everywhere from Bollywood classics and Punjabi pop to American rock and R&B. The group performs around the Chicagoland area and around the country. We are currently recording and producing our fifth studio album! Check out our website and listen to us on iTunes.

282295.description: Camp Kesem at Northwestern University is a local chapter of a national organization (Camp Kesem National) that supports children through and beyond their parent's cancer. CKNU hosts two weeks of free summer camp for over 150 children from the Chicagoland area who have been affected by a parent's cancer. Although our camps take place during the summer, throughout the year, our counselors fundraise, outreach to find campers, and get trained in order to prepare for the summer! Camp Kesem is a great organization for any students interested in children or summer camp, or are interested in making a meaningful impact through service! Watch this video to learn what we do here Check out our Facebook page to learn more!

914496.description: Campus Curlz will provide education by giving  free lectures and powerpoints titled ‘Natural Hair Inside and Out’ on our campus, schools and other public avenues as well as utilizing social media channels and the corporation website to provide facts, statistics and related data to raise awareness on healthy hair to eradicate the majority's lack of knowledge on the topic. We will also provide  events and programs including but not limited style parties where we demonstrate how to style hair, tabling events at an activity hour on campus, and dorm chats touching on topics including healthy hair, beauty, networking and navigating through college.  To maximize our impact, Campus Curlz will provide service by partnering with local non-profit organizations and participating in community events including but not limited to volunteering at local soup kitchens, elderly residential facilities, domestic abuse survivor centers, mentoring and tutoring  at local schools.

122559.description: Each quarter campusCATALYST recruits undergraduate students to provide consulting services for local nonprofits. Students take a cC designed for-credit seminar where they learn about consulting, nonprofit management and the social sector. Teams of 5 students are paired with a local nonprofit that needs assistance with strategic challenges. Each team is also mentored by a Kellogg MBA student for the quarter, who offers advice and guidance in the consulting process.

910064.description: Northwestern's Caribbean Student Alliance is an organization for students of Caribbean descent, as well as all members of the NU community who are interested in the dynamic culture. It seeks to explore and preserve the culture through many types of on-campus programming.

736401.description: The purpose of Carnaval is to provide a space where Northwestern students feel comfortable practicing the Portuguese language in a relaxed environment and to expand their knowledge of lusophone cultures. By encouraging discussions of topics ranging from everyday life to cultural phenomena, we hope that students will build on their understanding of the diversity and history behind the Portuguese language, and that this development will become part of a toolset for language learning. We aim to nurture students’ personal relationships with the language by learning from various materials and speakers. Ultimately, Carnaval will become a community of learning and explanation that will serve as an enriching complement to a traditional Portuguese curriculum.

660596.description: Welcome to Chair-ity! We, members of the Class of 2024, began this organization in the summer of 2020 in an effort to crowdfund "the Captain’s Chair" from the Northwestern Bookstore, but have since shifted our funding focus to raising money and awareness for topical issues worldwide. Our current goal is to bring together the University’s student populace (especially first-years) by promoting charitable efforts and creating bonding traditions for future first-year classes, especially as we deal with and prepare to come out of a global pandemic.   As a fledgling organization, we have many plans to get off the ground–events, fundraisers, and smaller experiences.  Chair-ity is all about welcoming every first-year and every other student that would like to be involved for the sake of both purpose and tradition.

107613.description: CSI is an international honor society that values academic and professional excellence in counseling. We promote a strong professional identity through members (professional counselors, counselor educators, and students) who contribute to the realization of a healthy society by fostering wellness and human dignity.

135979.description: Northwestern China Care is interested in supporting and saving the lives of abandoned Chinese orphans. We are an independent, student run club at Northwestern University, and a recognized China Care Club under the China Care Foundation, Inc and a partner of the Half the Sky Foundation. Northwestern China Care's mission is to sponsor education, surgeries, and medical treatments for orphans in China. Within the Chicago area, we aim to create and foster a stronger community with the adopted children and with China Care families by holding playgroups and a mentorship program for adopted orphans. The money we raise goes to support individual children, children with names and faces. Northwestern students have a chance to impact singular lives, one by one, whether that be by raising money, playing with kids at playgroups, or being a mentor to an adopted Chinese child. Though a student club in college seems trivial and minor with respect to the vastness of the orphan problem in China, Chinese orphans and adopted families gladly accept every small deed that is offered. Thus every donation, no matter how small or large, and every hour dedicated to supporting this cause can change lives.

284075.description: What we do: Volunteer - You will work with medical students and health professionals to provide free primary healthcare to the indigent public at health fairs and clinics. Interpreting is a further way get more involved clinical experience (conversational proficiency in Mandarin or Cantonese required as translator). Education - CTHI hopes to foster greater education of health-related issues on campus and in Chinatown. On campus, we have held speaker events and discussions. In Chinatown, we are starting outreach initiatives to connect to the public. Fundraising - In the past we hand-made and sold Chinese spring rolls and pastries to raise funds to buy medicine, equipment, and other medical supplies. New initiatives always welcome! No cooking or language experience needed Socials - We hold all types of socials, including dim sum outings, movie nights, game nights, etc! Come meet fellow CTHI members and have a good time. Apply to join the student board as a Junior Executive (Fall) and Executive Member (Spring). Our executive board coordinates volunteering activities and fundraisers. This is a great way to gain event planning experience and build communication and leadership skills!

937368.description: Formed in 2009, Chinese International Student Association is a cultural club that welcomes international chinese students and all friends who are interested in Chinese. It aims to promote the authentic Chinese culture on campus, while providing a sense of belonging for the international Chinese students, helping them in transition to college life in US. CISA also tries to connect the Northwestern students with the scholars/ visitors from China in order to gain understanding of Chinese society from a local perspective. Moreover, CISA is also promoting the brand of Northwestern University in China, helping to match Northwestern students to career opportunities in China.

985374.description: The Chinese Students Association is one of the first established Asian-American student groups at Northwestern. We aim to promote the awareness of Chinese culture on campus and elsewhere while encouraging a social environment for students of all backgrounds. Furthermore, we strive to bring service to our community. Our events are geared towards bringing together the Asian community while sharing our culture with others. Some annual events include: Celebrasia, bowling nights, dances, dinner parties, and hosting famous guest speakers.

698862.description: The purpose of this organization is to promote service, leadership, and fellowship within members in order to not only become aware of and impact their community, but also encourage personal growth.

217960.description: Circle of Women is an international student-led organization that supports girls' education in developing countries. We partner with local NGOs all over the world to work on projects, and plan events to fundraise and spread awareness.  We’re motivated by 3 things. First, the world still under invests in girls. Even though a lot of progress has been made in terms of providing access to education for girls, still, there have been groups of girls that have been left behind in the broad rises to access to education. These girls are typically in the most difficult to reach places -- think indigenous, rural, communities, whose intersectionality in terms of broad societal marginalization has excluded them from big waves and progress towards universal access to education. This means that still, the most vulnerable girls are often the first ones to miss out on educations when families have to make hard decisions about who to send to school.  Each project is tailored to the specific school and community; we take into consideration their needs rather than imposing our own agenda. Projects look different in each place. Some have focused on access like building dorms in Kenya, expanding or increasing quality of education like building computer labs in Peru or A-level classrooms in Tanzania This is a video of the perfect example of what we try to power through our partnerships. This is a video of Bertha’s story. Bertha is a graduate of Orkeeswa, a secondary school in rural Tanzania Circle of Women partnered with in 2015.

715427.description: The Northwestern University College Democrats serves as a campus hub for progressive thought and action. In an effort to increase student involvement in politics and voter turnout among college-aged students, we host events with distinguished keynote speakers every academic quarter, sponsor colloquia on campus, and organize a multitude of canvassing and outreach opportunities in Evanston and the greater Chicago area. In addition, we hold weekly meetings on campus, where we discuss current events, debate progressive ideals and policy, and, most importantly, build a strong community.

679592.description: College Feminists is the premier feminist and pro-choice organization on the Evanston Northwestern campus. We meet at the Women's Center, discussing issues ranging from domestic violence to the college hook-up scene. We believe that every woman should be able to make her own decisions regarding abortion and birth control and we seek to educate students and the community at large about their rights to such decisions. We also work to counteract negative images of women and work against gender stereotyping. We believe in a progressive, informed, and open-minded community. We hope to accomplish these goals by rallying, supporting and educating one another in the Northwestern Community and also by creating a network with other college campuses nationwide.

788370.description: College Republicans is Northwestern's conservative student organization that supports the ideals of the Republican Party. We host high-profile speakers, participate in campus debates and activities, and provide a variety of opportunities for all political backgrounds.  We bring speakers to campus who appeal to moderates, libertarians, objectivists, and conservatives of all colors, and all are welcome to attend meetings and events.

210945.description: The Northwestern Community Health Corps (CHC) is a grass roots student run organization that aims to empower individuals to better manage their health in Evanston and Skokie area.   CHC student volunteers launched and operate the Community Health Hub, a health resource desk at Evanston Public Library where they help community members navigate through their health related questions and connect individuals to existing health information and resources. In addition, through a unique partnership with the American Red Cross, CHC recruits and trains students to be trainers in CPR/First Aid/AED courses in order to provide these trainings free of charge to underserved populations in our community. CHC has formed partnerships with the Evanston and Skokie Public Libraries, Erie Family Health Center, Asian Human Services, the Evanston and Skokie Health Departments, and community health leaders.

234212.description: Started in the spring of 2008, CASE is a student organization at Northwestern University dedicated to providing pro bono consulting advice to Northwestern-based organizations. Our work is grounded in our belief in the power of Northwestern University organizations to make a visible difference in our community, and we seek to harness our intellectual capital to help them become more efficient, active, and impactful. The way we approach this mission is two-fold. First, we provide measurable results to our clients. We stand behind our work 100%, and we follow through with our clients to ensure our recommendations are fully implemented. Second, we provide the best possible learning experience for our consultants. Through ‘hands-on’ consulting experience, we develop our members to be well-rounded, analytical minds.

917567.description: The CTSS is an undergraduate initiative at Northwestern supported by the Offices of the President, the Provost, and the Division of Student Affairs. Our board of students seeks to identify and secure the most forward-thinking minds of our generation to speak to the Northwestern community on the purpose and value of a university education in today's world.

388179.description: To explore different ingredients and cooking techniques To learn the basics of kitchen equipment, safety and maintenance To learn and experiment with new recipes, flavors, and presentation methods To experience a range of cultures through cuisine To develop a greater appreciation of high quality food And above all, to create a passion in people for food.

898686.description: C.O.P.E. unites and empowers college students in their initiatives to fight cancer through public awareness, fundraising, and patient support (volunteering) for a variety of cancer-related organizations. It is a group devoted to developing leadership, providing service with compassion and maturity, and positively impacting university and national medical communities. We are a creative, diverse, and dynamic bunch, and love new members to jump in at anytime.

876396.description: We provide a platform for all the students and scholars from Northwestern University to discuss and explore issues on current economic, political and cultural situations, as well as to catalyze further understanding of business and economy relations between China and other countries. We bring in professors and professionals of diverse backgrounds and fields to share opinions and develop cross-border understanding on contemporary China.

647538.description: Dale Duro Latin Dance Co. (DDLDC), Northwestern’s Latin dance team, is an inclusive dance group started in 2018 composed of Latin culture appreciators of all backgrounds and skill levels. We teach free workshops of varied Latin dance styles throughout each quarter, host community bonding events like karaoke nights and movie nights, and perform in our BIG annual spring show where we showcase our talents in salsa, bachata, merengue, flamenco, cumbia, reggaeton and more. We hope to continue fostering a supportive environment where we can all grow as Latin dancers, all while enriching and strengthening our perspective on Latin culture.

264446.description: Dead City Productions is a group of Northwestern students, alumni, and their guests who participate in various types of gaming in the form of live-action roleplaying, strategic board-gaming, and other entertaining games.  We are open to anyone willing to participate — no experience necessary!  Live-action roleplaying, or LARPing, is ideal for gamers as well as actors who enjoy the more improvisational side of acting.  Dead City Productions' LARP takes place in the form of a continuing, 10-game-long story occurring roughly every other week.  We also occasionally host one-shot games, in which a story begins and is resolved in the course of one evening-long game session.  All of our games are run using White Wolf's Vampire: The Requiem system, which is sometimes supplemented with other White Wolf systems depending on the needs of the storytelling team.

958921.description: Deeva is a nationally-recognized, all-female competitive dance team that blends the best of Indian classical, Bollywood, folk, ballet, lyrical, and hip-hop. Founded in 2001, the team has a unique mission: to generate and participate in an intercultural dialogue through dance. Each dancer brings a unique background from the diverse regions of South Asia and knowledge of a variety of dance styles from all over the world. By choreographing dances that mix cultures, Deeva is excited to not only bring increased cultural awareness to the student body, but to have a cultural exchange through dance.

243919.description: Delta Sigma Pi is Northwestern's premier co-ed business fraternity.  Our activities focus on three aspects: Professional, Social, and Community Service.   We develop our members professionally through a wide range of activities and career related workshops.  Past events have included a pro-bono consulting panel with a top consulting firm, a stock competition (open to the entire NU community), guest speakers, site visits, and courses on resume building, interviewing, and networking. We also provide several leadership positions and a connection to the vast alumni base of the national organization.    Through Delta Sigma Pi, you will develop lasting relationships with brothers who share a common interest. Our members form a community and support each other in professional and academic endeavors.  We hold several social events per quarter and perform community service in the Evanston/Chicagoland area.

493162.description: Design for America (DFA) is an award-winning nationwide network of interdisciplinary student teams and community members using design to create local and social impact. DFA teaches human centered design to young adults and collaborating community partners through extra-curricular, university based, student led design studios to look locally, create fervently and act fearlessly. DFA currently tackles national challenges in Education, Health, Economy and Environment. We take applications for new projects every quarter! Email northwestern@designforamerica.com to get the application.

571599.description: Desire to Aspire is a mentorship program that focuses on serving girls and young women. Mentors visit the girls after school weekly for an hour and participate in a variety of activities that enhance problem solving skills, confidence, coping strategies, and more. Mentors also help plan fun field trips for the girls outside of weekly meetings.

407926.description: DISC started as a student group in 2017 with the goal of expanding Northwestern students' perceptions of the capabilities of technology. Since then, we've gathered a diverse group of student leaders interested in using technology to make a positive impact on the world. We recognize the power of collaboration across difference, and look for the right balance of technical and non-technical skills when we work together. We do this by assembling project teams of hardworking students, and challenging them to grow as they work for our clients.

773270.description: The Dolphin Show is a non-profit student theatre organization that annually produces America's largest student-produced musical. Having evolved from a swim team fundraiser in the 1940's to an annual professional-caliber musical production, The Dolphin Show celebrates the diverse talents of the Northwestern University undergraduate community by providing opportunities to learn and excel in all artistic and administrative fields of non-profit theatre. The Dolphin Show additionally involves the greater Chicago area communities through outreach programming. Successful Dolphin Show Alumni include actors David Schwimmer, Warren Beatty and former Miss America Kate Shindle.

189200.description: EWH NU is part of a larger national organization that is headquartered in Chapel Hill, NC and is comprised of about 50 chapter worldwide. EWH works with university-based biomedical engineers, industry professionals, charities that manage donated medical equipment, the international health community and developing countries to combine innovation in appropriate technology with direct support to medical technology management, maintenance and repair. To learn more visit www.ewh.org

763454.description: Engineers for a Sustainable World (ESW-NU) is an action-based group, mobilizing students through education, training, and hands-on projects related to environmental sustainability. Membership is not limited to engineers, but rather includes students from all schools at Northwestern, and entails working in student teams with faculty and professional advisers to further sustainability both locally and internationally. Our projects range in focus from renewable energy to clean drinking water, green infrastructure, and much more. For more information, please contact us at contact.eswnu@gmail.com!

888044.description: Engineers Without Borders-Northwestern works cooperatively with international communities to add engineering expertise to community-driven projects that address the community's most prevalent problems. Members of EWB-NU work throughout the academic year to brainstorm, research, survey, design, and prototype solutions to these problems, while working closely with a group of professional engineering mentors, an NGO, and most importantly, the partner community. These designs range from household necessities, to sanitation needs, to civil works, and beyond. Approximately once a year, EWB-NU sends a group of students and mentors to the community we work with to conduct further research and/or implement a phase of the project while building relationships with the members of the community. EWB-NU also engages with the Northwestern, Evanston, and Chicago communities in to promote sustainability, engineering education, and stronger bonds between Northwestern and our surrounding communities. We do this through regular on-campus events, mentorship of local Chicago middle schools, and our developing service projects. We are always looking to increase the outreach that we do, so if you have ideas or a connection you would like to make, please reach out! EWB-NU welcomes students of all academic backgrounds who are interested working toward making a positive impact on the world. Students gain experience in project management and leadership, design, teamwork, cross-cultural communication, fundraising, and interdisciplinary problem solving.

838171.description: The Environmental Engineering Undergraduate Society (EnvEUS) at Northwestern gives students the opportunity to meet other Environmental Engineering students, participate in career development events, and apply technical skills outside of the classroom.
